      <div class="tab-content active" id="tab-bp-sql">
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🏗️</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Use CTEs over nested subqueries</div>
          <div class="bp-text">CTEs make logic readable and debuggable. If a query has more than 2 levels of nesting, refactor to WITH clauses. Future-you (and your colleagues) will thank you.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">⚡</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Filter early with WHERE, not late</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Apply WHERE conditions before JOINs wherever possible. Joining 10M rows then filtering is 100x slower than filtering to 100K rows then joining. Always use EXPLAIN ANALYZE to verify query plans.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🎯</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Never SELECT * in production</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Always specify columns. SELECT * transfers unnecessary data, breaks when schema changes, and prevents the optimizer from using column-level statistics. Name what you need.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🔢</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Test for duplicates before every JOIN</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Run <code style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;color:var(--teal)">SELECT key, COUNT(*) FROM table GROUP BY key HAVING COUNT(*) > 1</code> on join keys. A many-to-many JOIN silently explodes your row count and corrupts metrics.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">📝</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Comment your business logic, not the syntax</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Comment WHY, not WHAT. "-- Count only paid users (excludes free tier per Finance definition)" is useful. "-- COUNT the users" is not.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🔒</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Validate row counts at every step</div>
          <div class="bp-text">After each transformation, verify: did the row count change? Should it have? A quick SELECT COUNT(*) after each CTE step prevents silent data quality bugs.</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tab-content" id="tab-bp-py">
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🐼</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Never loop over DataFrame rows</div>
          <div class="bp-text">df.iterrows() on a 1M-row dataframe takes minutes. Use vectorized operations (df['col'] * 2), apply(), or numpy where(). Vectorization uses C under the hood — orders of magnitude faster.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🧹</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Handle dtypes explicitly when reading data</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Always specify dtype={'id': str, 'amount': float} in read_csv. Auto-detection silently converts IDs with leading zeros to integers, breaking your analysis.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">📁</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Structure notebooks: EDA → Clean → Analyze → Visualize</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Notebooks become unmaintainable without structure. Use headers as section markers. Keep data loading at the top. Never mix cleaning code with visualization code — reviewers (and you) will get lost.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🔄</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Don't modify the original DataFrame — use copies</div>
          <div class="bp-text">df_clean = df.copy() before any transformations. Accidentally modifying the source DataFrame mid-analysis is one of the most common hard-to-debug bugs.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">📊</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Always add titles and axis labels to charts</div>
          <div class="bp-text">A chart without a title is not a deliverable. Add plt.title(), plt.xlabel(), plt.ylabel() and annotate outliers/key data points. Stakeholders read the title first.</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tab-content" id="tab-bp-analysis">
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🎯</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Start with the question, not the data</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Define the business question precisely before opening a dataset. "Revenue is down" is not a question. "Why did checkout conversion drop on mobile in the last 14 days?" is. This determines which data you need.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">📐</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Disaggregate every aggregate</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Average hides distributions. Always segment: by time, geography, user segment, device, cohort. A 5% average conversion rate might be 12% on desktop and 2% on mobile — completely different problems.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">⚖️</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Correlation ≠ Causation — always say so</div>
          <div class="bp-text">When presenting findings, explicitly state when you're showing correlation vs establishing causation. "Users who use Feature X have higher retention" ≠ "Feature X causes higher retention." This builds analytical credibility.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">🚦</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">Know your denominators</div>
          <div class="bp-text">15% conversion rate means nothing without the denominator. 15% of what? Unique visitors? Sessions? Users who saw the CTA? Mismatched denominators cause wrong conclusions.</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="bp-item">
          <div class="bp-icon">📋</div>
          <div><div class="bp-title">MECE your analysis frameworks</div>
          <div class="bp-text">Break problems into Mutually Exclusive, Collectively Exhaustive segments. Revenue = (New customers × AOV) + (Returning customers × AOV). If these two add up to total, you haven't missed any segment.</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
